If self_name is declared as a non-const pointer (e.g. char *self_name) but is never modified (e.g. it points to argv[0] or a string literal), this violates MISRA C 2023 Rule 8.13 — the pointer should be declared const char *self_name. The printf call itself is fine, but the underlying declaration must be const-qualified when possible.
